# Enterprise Architecture Constitution (Mandatory)

Full text: `docs/ENTERPRISE_ARCHITECTURE_CONSTITUTION.md`

This constitution has **higher priority than individual feature requests**.

## Before ANY implementation

1. Inspect the whole system first (Platform Owner, Company Administration, auth, permissions, licensing, seats, workspaces, orgs, audit, history, i18n, nav, repos, DB, actions, UI, policies, workflows).
2. Read `docs/PROJECT_BIBLE.md`, `docs/MASTER_PRD.md`, `docs/SYSTEM_ARCHITECTURE.md` (or `architecture/SYSTEM_ARCHITECTURE.md`) when relevant.
3. Answer reuse questions: Does it exist? Extend? Reuse? Compose? Generalize? Only if all are NO may new code be introduced.

## Absolute prohibitions

- Do not sacrifice architecture for speed.
- Do not create competing implementations of auth, audit, history, timeline, activity, localization, permissions, delete/restore/lifecycle/retention, seats, licensing, navigation, theme, notifications, validation, search, export/import.
- Do not create new tables / repositories / services unless existing ones cannot support the requirement — document justification if unavoidable.
- Do not duplicate Platform Owner Console or build a second Company Administration platform (Company Admin = permission-scoped subset of Platform capabilities).
- Do not create another audit system — reuse `emitAuditEvent()` and `audit_logs`.
- Do not create another history/timeline/activity system — derive version history from audit.
- Never hardcode UI strings — every feature must ship EN / AZ / RU / TR.
- Every UI must be responsive (desktop/laptop/tablet/mobile), dark-mode safe, no horizontal scroll.

## Decision rule

When approaches are equivalent, choose the one that reduces complexity and duplicated state, reuses infrastructure, preserves business logic, avoids new persistence, and improves maintainability.

## Conflict handling

If a request violates this constitution: **STOP**, explain the conflict, propose an architecture-compliant alternative.

## After implementation

Verify no duplicates, no regressions, localization complete (4 languages), responsive, dark mode, security, and architecture consistency. Features must feel native to one cohesive enterprise platform.
